Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document:

**Document Structure**

Let's assume we have a LaTeX document named `main.tex` with the following structure:
```tex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

\subsection{Background}
\label{sec:introduction:bg}

\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}

\subsection{Experimental Design}
\label{sec:methods:experimental-design}

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Data Analysis}
\label{sec:results:data-analysis}

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

\end{document}
```
**Generating the Table of Contents**

To generate the TOC, we need to use the `\tableofcontents` command, which is part of the `toc` package. We also need to use `\section`, `\subsection`, etc. commands to define the headings.

**Adding the `toc` Package**

Add the following line at the beginning of your document:
```tex
\usepackage{toc}
```
This package provides the necessary commands to generate the TOC.

**Using `\tableofcontents`**

Add the following line after the `\begin{document}` command:
```tex
\tableofcontents
```
This command tells LaTeX to generate the TOC.

**Output**

When you compile the document, LaTeX will generate a table of contents with the following output:
```
Table of Contents

Introduction ............................................... 1
    Background ............................................... 1

Methods ................................................... 2
    Experimental Design ................................... 2

Results ................................................... 3
    Data Analysis ....................................... 3

Conclusion ............................................... 4

```
**How it Works**

LaTeX uses the `\section`, `\subsection`, etc. commands to define the headings in the document. When we use `\tableofcontents`, LaTeX scans the document and extracts the headings, creating a table of contents with the corresponding page numbers.

Note that you can customize the appearance of the TOC by using various options available in the `toc` package. For example, you can change the font size, spacing, and formatting of the TOC entries using commands like `\setcounter`, `\renewcommand`, etc.

