    cout << "Common elements are: ";
    findCommonElements(arr1, arr2, m, n);
    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we iterate through both arrays using two pointers `i` and `j`. If `arr1[i]` equals `arr2[j]`, we print the common element and increment both `i` and `j`. If `arr1[i]` is less than `arr2[j]`, we increment `i`. If `arr1[i]` is greater than `arr2[j]`, we increment `j`. This way, we ensure that we don't miss any common elements.

